The latest Ebola category-four case, the one in Dallas, was an American airline employee. Officials had previously identified the person only as a former Dallas-area resident who had recently returned from Africa.

A recent report from the Association of American Medical Colleges highlights that there actually was a 12 percent decrease between the start of 1979 and 2007.

The cause of the drop seems clear. Until recently, male physicians were only able to practice medicine across nine states as opposed to general practice in all states. Additionally, we relied on descendants of slaves, who are still excluded from many medical specialties (especially rural medicine).

While the decline in male medical school enrollment comes as a shock, it might not actually be total. Many of the umbrella medical schools generate a lot of their students out of underserved populations. For example, medical schools in rural areas have historically charged higher tuition fees – before canceling them and reimbursing them in the form of tuition credit. Medical schools have also been able to convince more people to take internships, which in turn attract more students.

Because of those advantages, African-American males might actually be more likely to enroll in medical school and then default out of medical school. Even when schools get better and more schools reverse tuition credit policies, the decline will still be high. If African-American males are enrolling in undergraduate medical school, but dropping out, then it will take a considerable amount of time to repair the problem. Eventually, these individuals will graduate, and their presence will offer some value to the medical community.

Despite the fact that African-American men still make up less than 5 percent of medical students, these men could actually be a valuable resource for the rest of us. American Health Care Act exposes their importance, in case we ever run into an oncoming epidemic of patient access to medical care. This means that we should aim to increase their numbers.
